This is a list of some of the {{ill|Kujūku Ōji|fr|Kujūku Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|lt=99 ōji Shrines|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|qq=}} on the [[Kumano Kodō]]. This article covers the shrines in the regions of Kaizuka.
==Overview== {{Shrine | Name = {{ill|Kujūku Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|qq=}} | image = | location = {{ill|Kishiwada, Osaka|ja|岸和田市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishiwada, Osaka|qq=}} and {{ill|Kaizuka, Osaka|ja|貝塚市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaizuka, Osaka|qq=}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Osaka Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan | coordinates = | deity = | Affiliation = {{ill|Kumano Kōdō|ja|熊野古道|1=Kumano Kodō|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kōdō|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kodō|qq=}} - {{ill|Kumano Pilgrimage|ja|熊野信仰|1=Kumano Three Shrines|lt=Kumano faith|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Pilgrimage|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Three Shrines|qq=}} | Established = | Map = }}
This article covers the '''{{ill|Kujūku Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|qq=}}''' shrines located within {{ill|Kishiwada, Osaka|ja|岸和田市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishiwada, Osaka|qq=}} and {{ill|Kaizuka, Osaka|ja|貝塚市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kaizuka, Osaka|qq=}}, which were part of the historic pilgrimage route to {{ill|Kumano Sanzan|ja|熊野三山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Sanzan|qq=}} along the {{ill|Kumano Kōdō|ja|熊野古道|1=Kumano Kodō|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kōdō|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kodō|qq=}}.
== Overview of Kujūku Ōji == {{Main|{{ill|Kujūku Ōji|ja|九十九王子|1=Kujūku Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|1=Kujūku Ōji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kujūku Ōji|qq=}}}}
The Kujūku Ōji shrines refer to a group of sacred sites along the {{ill|Kumano Kōdō|ja|熊野古道|1=Kumano Kodō|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kōdō|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kodō|qq=}}, especially the {{ill|Kiiji|ja|紀伊路|1=Kiiji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiiji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiiji|qq=}} route, established during the 12th and 13th centuries by {{ill|Kumano Shugendō|ja|熊野修験|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Shugendō|qq=}} practitioners. These shrines served to protect pilgrims, including members of the imperial family and nobility, on their journeys to the sacred sites of Kumano.
Following the decline of the {{ill|Kumano Pilgrimage|ja|熊野詣|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Pilgrimage|qq=}} after the {{ill|Jōkyū War|ja|承久の乱|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōkyū War|qq=}} in 1221, many of these shrines fell into disrepair. Despite some restoration efforts during the Edo period by the {{ill|Kishū Domain|ja|紀州藩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishū Domain|qq=}}, many shrines were lost due to urbanization and the State Shinto reforms of the Meiji era.
This article focuses on the Kujūku Ōji shrines identified within Kishiwada and Kaizuka.
== Kujūku Ōji Shrines == There is one known Ōji shrine in Kishiwada and three in Kaizuka.
=== {{ill|Ikeda Ōji|ja|池田王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikeda Ōji|qq=}} === Located near {{ill|Kumeda Station|ja|久米田駅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumeda Station|qq=}} on the {{ill|Hanwa Line|ja|阪和線|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanwa Line|qq=}}, the former site of Ikeda Ōji is now private land in Shimo-Ikeda, Kishiwada. The shrine was believed to be associated with {{ill|Sekigawa Shrine (Kishiwada|ja|積川神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekigawa Shrine (Kishiwada|qq=}} and was merged into {{ill|Yagi Shrine|ja|夜疑神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yagi Shrine|qq=}} during the Meiji period.
=== {{ill|Asokawa Ōji|ja|麻生川王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asokawa Ōji|qq=}} === Also known as Aso River Ōji, it was merged into {{ill|Arimaku Shrine|ja|阿里莫神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Arimaku Shrine|qq=}} in Kaizuka in 1909. The shrine was venerated by the Handa community, and although its original location is now occupied by a factory, nearby landmarks commemorate its historical significance.
=== {{ill|Kuramochi Ōji|ja|鞍持王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuramochi Ōji|qq=}} === Merged into {{ill|Minami Kogi Shrine|ja|南近義神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minami Kogi Shrine|qq=}} in Kaizuka in 1907, the former shrine site still has a small torii gate and shrine structure. Some historical records suggest alternative locations, including near {{ill|Shōfuku-ji (Kaizuka|ja|正福寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōfuku-ji (Kaizuka|qq=}}.
=== {{ill|Kogi Ōji|ja|近木王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kogi Ōji|qq=}} === Also known as Kogi Shin Ōji, it was merged into Minami Kogi Shrine in the late Meiji era. The former shrine site is debated, with possible locations near {{ill|Zenshō-ji (Kaizuka|ja|善正寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenshō-ji (Kaizuka|qq=}} or the former {{ill|Kumano Shrine (Kaizuka|ja|熊野神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Shrine (Kaizuka|qq=}} site.
