Following the decline of the {{ill|Kumano Pilgrimage|ja|熊野詣|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Pilgrimage|qq=}} after the {{ill|Jōkyū War|ja|承久の乱|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jōkyū War|qq=}} in 1221, many of these shrines fell into disrepair. Despite some restoration efforts during the Edo period by the {{ill|Kishū Domain|ja|紀州藩|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kishū Domain|qq=}}, many shrines were lost due to urbanization and the State Shinto reforms of the Meiji era.
This article focuses on the Kujūku Ōji shrines identified within Kishiwada and Kaizuka.
== Kujūku Ōji Shrines == There is one known Ōji shrine in Kishiwada and three in Kaizuka.
=== {{ill|List of Kujūku Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=List of Kujūku Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=Ikeda Ōji|ja|池田王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikeda Ōji|qq=}} === Located near {{ill|Kumeda Station|ja|久米田駅|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumeda Station|qq=}} on the {{ill|Hanwa Line|ja|阪和線|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hanwa Line|qq=}}, the former site of Ikeda Ōji is now private land in Shimo-Ikeda, Kishiwada. The shrine was believed to be associated with {{ill|Sekigawa Shrine (Kishiwada|ja|積川神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekigawa Shrine (Kishiwada|qq=}} and was merged into {{ill|Yagi Shrine|ja|夜疑神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yagi Shrine|qq=}} during the Meiji period.
=== {{ill|List of Kujūku Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=List of Kujūku Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=Asokawa Ōji|ja|麻生川王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asokawa Ōji|qq=}} === Also known as Aso River Ōji, it was merged into {{ill|Arimaku Shrine|ja|阿里莫神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Arimaku Shrine|qq=}} in Kaizuka in 1909. The shrine was venerated by the Handa community, and although its original location is now occupied by a factory, nearby landmarks commemorate its historical significance.
=== {{ill|Kuramochi Ōji|ja|鞍持王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuramochi Ōji|qq=}} === Merged into {{ill|Minami Kogi Shrine|ja|南近義神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minami Kogi Shrine|qq=}} in Kaizuka in 1907, the former shrine site still has a small torii gate and shrine structure. Some historical records suggest alternative locations, including near {{ill|Shōfuku-ji (Kaizuka|ja|正福寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōfuku-ji (Kaizuka|qq=}}.
=== {{ill|List of Kujūku Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=List of Kujūku Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=Kogi Ōji|ja|近木王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kogi Ōji|qq=}} === Also known as Kogi Shin Ōji, it was merged into Minami Kogi Shrine in the late Meiji era. The former shrine site is debated, with possible locations near {{ill|Zenshō-ji (Kaizuka|ja|善正寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenshō-ji (Kaizuka|qq=}} or the former {{ill|Kumano Shrine (Kaizuka|ja|熊野神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Shrine (Kaizuka|qq=}} site.
