{{afc comment|Wikidata entry [[d:Q11370044]] Wikidata name: (none) [[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 07:52, 11 June 2025 (UTC)}} This is a list of some of the {{ill|Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|fr|Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|ja|九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=99 ōji Shrines|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}} on the [[Kumano Kodō]]. This article covers the shrines in the regions of Kaizuka.
==Overview== {{Infobox religious building| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | Name = {{ill|Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|ja|九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}} | image = | location = [[:en:Kishiwada, Osaka|Kishiwada, Osaka]] and [[:en:Kaizuka, Osaka|Kaizuka, Osaka]], [[:en:Osaka Prefecture|Osaka Prefecture]], Japan | coordinates = | deity = | Affiliation = [[:en:Kumano Kodō|Kumano Kodō]] - {{ill|Kumano Pilgrimage|ja|熊野信仰|1=Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano Three Shrines|lt=Kumano faith|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Pilgrimage|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Three Shrines|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 熊野三山}} | Established = | Map = | location = {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|qid=Q122723}} }}
This article covers the '''{{ill|Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|ja|九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}}''' shrines located within [[:en:Kishiwada, Osaka|Kishiwada, Osaka]] and [[:en:Kaizuka, Osaka|Kaizuka, Osaka]], which were part of the historic pilgrimage route to {{ill|Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano Sanzan|ja|熊野三山|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Sanzan|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} along the [[:en:Kumano Kodō|Kumano Kodō]].
== Overview of Ninety-Nine Ōji == {{Main|{{ill|Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|ja|九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|2=ja|3=九十九王子|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|4=fr|5=Kujūkuōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|1=Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|13=User:Immanuelle/Ninety-Nine Ōji|lt=Ninety-Nine Ōji|qq=}}}}
The Ninety-Nine Ōji shrines refer to a group of sacred sites along the [[:en:Kumano Kodō|Kumano Kodō]], especially the {{ill|Kiiji|ja|紀伊路|1=Kiiji|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiiji|13=User:Immanuelle/Kiiji|qq=}} route, established during the 12th and 13th centuries by {{ill|Kumano Shugendō|ja|熊野修験|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Shugendō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} practitioners. These shrines served to protect pilgrims, including members of the imperial family and nobility, on their journeys to the sacred sites of Kumano.
Following the decline of the {{ill|Kumano Pilgrimage|ja|熊野詣|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Pilgrimage|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 熊野三山}} after the [[:en:Jōkyū War|Jōkyū War]] in 1221, many of these shrines fell into disrepair. Despite some restoration efforts during the Edo period by the [[:en:Kishū Domain|Kishū Domain]], many shrines were lost due to urbanization and the State Shinto reforms of the Meiji era.
This article focuses on the Ninety-Nine Ōji shrines identified within Kishiwada and Kaizuka.
== Ninety-Nine Ōji Shrines == There is one known Ōji shrine in Kishiwada and three in Kaizuka.
=== {{ill|List of Ninety-Nine Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=List of Ninety-Nine Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=Ikeda Ōji|ja|池田王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikeda Ōji|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 九十九王子 (岸和田市・貝塚市)}} === Located near [[:en:Kumeda Station|Kumeda Station]] on the [[:en:Hanwa Line|Hanwa Line]], the former site of Ikeda Ōji is now private land in Shimo-Ikeda, Kishiwada. The shrine was believed to be associated with {{ill|Sekigawa Shrine (Kishiwada|ja|積川神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sekigawa Shrine (Kishiwada|qq=}} and was merged into {{ill|Yagi Shrine|ja|夜疑神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yagi Shrine|qq=}} during the Meiji period.
=== {{ill|List of Ninety-Nine Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=List of Ninety-Nine Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=Asokawa Ōji|ja|麻生川王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Asokawa Ōji|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 九十九王子 (岸和田市・貝塚市)}} === Also known as Aso River Ōji, it was merged into {{ill|Arimaku Shrine|ja|阿里莫神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Arimaku Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} in Kaizuka in 1909. The shrine was venerated by the Handa community, and although its original location is now occupied by a factory, nearby landmarks commemorate its historical significance.
=== {{ill|List of Ninety-Nine Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=List of Ninety-Nine Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=Kuramochi Ōji|ja|鞍持王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuramochi Ōji|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 九十九王子 (岸和田市・貝塚市)}} === Merged into {{ill|Minami Kogi Shrine|ja|南近義神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minami Kogi Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} in Kaizuka in 1907, the former shrine site still has a small torii gate and shrine structure. Some historical records suggest alternative locations, including near {{ill|Shōfuku-ji (Kaizuka|ja|正福寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōfuku-ji (Kaizuka|qq=}}.
=== {{ill|List of Ninety-Nine Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=List of Ninety-Nine Ōji (Kaizuka)|lt=Kogi Ōji|ja|近木王子|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kogi Ōji|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 九十九王子 (岸和田市・貝塚市)}} === Also known as Kogi Shin Ōji, it was merged into Minami Kogi Shrine in the late Meiji era. The former shrine site is debated, with possible locations near {{ill|Zenshō-ji (Kaizuka|ja|善正寺|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zenshō-ji (Kaizuka|qq=}} or the former [[:en:Kumano shrine|Kumano Shrine (Kaizuka]] site.
